1360","1324–1355":"1324–1355","1337–1386":"1337–1386","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1875–Female":"1875–Zesnulá","–Male":"Zesnulý","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Zesnulá","after about 1307":"po okolo 1307","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1875":"1875","1324":"1324","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","Abt 1342":"okolo 1342","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","1342":"1342","1386":"1386","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Skipton, York, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Hartlepool, Hartlepool, UK":"Hartlepool, Durham, Anglie, United Kingdom","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1307–1360":"1307–1360","1324–1355":"1324–1355","1337–1386":"1337–1386","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1875–Female":"1875–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Afdød","after about 1307":"efter omkring 1307","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1875":"1875","1324":"1324","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","Abt 1342":"omkring 1342","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","1342":"1342","1386":"1386","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Skipton, York, England":"Skipton, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","Hartlepool, Hartlepool, UK":"Hartlepool, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1307–1360":"1307–1360","1324–1355":"1324–1355","1337–1386":"1337–1386","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1875–Female":"1875–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Overleden","after about 1307":"na circa 1307","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1875":"1875","1324":"1324","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","Abt 1342":"circa 1342","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","1342":"1342","1386":"1386","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Skipton, York, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hartlepool, Hartlepool, UK":"Hartlepool, Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1307–1360":"1307–1360","1324–1355":"1324–1355","1337–1386":"1337–1386","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1875–Female":"1875–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","after about 1307":"after about 1307","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1875":"1875","1324":"1324","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","Abt 1342":"about 1342","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","1342":"1342","1386":"1386","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Skipton, York, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Hartlepool, Hartlepool, UK":"Hartlepool, Durham, England, United Kingdom","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lambert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, Walloon, Dutch, German, Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In England, the native Old English form <i>Landbeorht</i> was replaced by <i>Lambert</i>, the Continental form of the name that was taken to England by the Normans from France. The name gained wider currency in Britain in the Middle Ages with the immigration of weavers from Flanders, among whom Saint Lambert or Lamprecht, bishop of Maastricht in around 700, was a popular cult figure. In Italy the name was popularized in the Middle Ages as a result of the fame of Lambert I and II, Dukes of Spoleto and Holy Roman Emperors. <i>Lambert</i> is the second most frequent surname in Wallonia. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Slovenian <b>Lampret</b> and <b>Lampreht</b> (see also   Lampert  ).","History: Aubin Lambert <i>dit</i> Champagne from Tourouvre in Orne, France, married Élisabeth Aubert in Quebec City, QC, in 1670; see also   Champagne  . Eustache Lambert from Boulogne-sur-Mer in Pas-de-Calais, France, married Marie Laurence in France <i>c.</i> 1656, died in Quebec City, QC, in 1673. Pierre Lambert from Fourmetot in Eure, France, married Marie Normand in Quebec City, QC, in 1680. Augustin Hébert <i>dit</i> Lambert, a descendant of Augustin Hébert from Paris, France, married Françoise Petit in Varennes, QC, in 1761. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Lambers","meanings":["Dutch: patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberth","meanings":["English: variant of   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lambertus","meanings":["German and Dutch: humanistic name, Latinized form of the personal name   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Antonio, Carlo, Gaetano, Luciano, Amedeo, Angelo, Biagio, Domenic, Donato, Enrico, Gino, Iolanda.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Lamberto</i>, an equivalent of   Lambert  . This surname is also found in Corsica and southern France.","German and Dutch: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  , using the genitive of its Latinized form   Lambertus  ."]},{"name":"Lamberty","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ana, Dimas, Jose, Juan, Altagracia, Angel, Blanca, Efrain, Fernando, Jaime, Ramon.","German and French: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  , from <i>Lamberti</i>, the genitive of its Latinized form   Lambertus  . Compare   Lamberti   2."]},{"name":"Lambertz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Heinz, Erna, Johann, Ralf.","North German: patronymic from   Lambert  ."]},{"name":"Lamberto","meanings":["Italian and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Lamberto</i> (see   Lambert  )."]},{"name":"Lampert","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, and Slovak; Hungarian (<b>Lampért</b>): variant of   Lambert  . In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed some cognates from other languages, for example Slovenian <b>Lampret</b> and <b>Lampreht</b>.","English: variant of <b>Lambard</b>, an occupational name from Middle English <i>lambherd</i>, <i>lambhird</i>, <i>lambhurd</i> ‘lamb-herd’ (Old English <i>lamb</i> + <i>hierde</i>)."]},{"name":"Lambertsen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik.","Dutch, Danish, North German, and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Lambert  . This surname has died out in the Netherlands.","History: Cornelius Lambertsen came from Utrecht, the Netherlands, arriving at New Amsterdam in New Netherland (now New York City, NY) in 1642."]},{"name":"Lamb","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Lamb</i>, a pet form of   Lambert  .","English: nickname for a meek and inoffensive person, from Middle English <i>lamb</i>, or a metonymic occupational name for a keeper of lambs. See also   Lamm  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luain</b> ‘descendant of the warrior’, formerly Anglicized as <b>O'Loan</b> (see   Lane   3). MacLysaght comments: \"The form <b>Lamb(e)</b>, which results from a more than usually absurd pseudo-translation (<i>uan</i> ‘lamb’), is now much more numerous than <i>O'Loan</i> itself.\"."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":8,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":21,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":30,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Lambert was born in 1307, in Durham, England, his father, William Lambert, was 11304 and his mother, Jane Cresey, was 31. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Isabel Lambert. He died in 1360, in Hartlepool, Durham, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1307–1360":"1307–1360","1324–1355":"1324–1355","1337–1386":"1337–1386","1342–1411":"1342–1411","1875–Female":"1875–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1272–1307":"1272–1307","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","after about 1307":"umbes pärast 1307","1360":"1360","1272":"1272","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1875":"1875","1324":"1324","1411":"1411","1355":"1355","Abt 1342":"umbes 1342","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","1342":"1342","1386":"1386","1307":"1307","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Skipton, York, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hartlepool, Hartlepool, UK":"Hartlepool, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Owlton, Durham, England":"Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1307–1360":"1307–1